## `<file-level: imports>`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-interop-1 -->

### Purpose
End-to-end tests that run real tools (`git`, `rsync`, `tar`, `rg`, vim's atomic-save dance) against a FUSE mount. These are the tests that fail when an obscure POSIX corner is wrong — an editor can't save, git can't commit, rsync loses metadata. All `<!-- trace: skipped -->` — the correctness contract is "the tool exits 0 and produces the expected output", which is not derivable from library specs alone.

### Implementation Notes

```python
import os
import shutil
import subprocess
import pytest

pytestmark = pytest.mark.fuse

HAS_GIT = shutil.which("git") is not None
HAS_RSYNC = shutil.which("rsync") is not None
HAS_RG = shutil.which("rg") is not None
HAS_TAR = shutil.which("tar") is not None
```

---

## `test_interop_git_init_add_commit(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-interop-2 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: external tool behavior -->

### Purpose
`git init && git add . && git commit -m msg` succeeds inside the mount. Verifies symlinks (git's `.git/HEAD`), hard links (git's objects dir), O_EXCL creation (git's lockfiles), rename atomicity.

### Postconditions

```python
if not HAS_GIT:
    pytest.skip("git not installed")

workdir = mount / "repo"
workdir.mkdir()

subprocess.run(["git", "-C", str(workdir), "init", "--quiet"], check=True)
subprocess.run(["git", "-C", str(workdir), "config", "user.email", "t@t"], check=True)
subprocess.run(["git", "-C", str(workdir), "config", "user.name", "t"], check=True)

(workdir / "file.txt").write_text("hello\n")
subprocess.run(["git", "-C", str(workdir), "add", "file.txt"], check=True)
subprocess.run(["git", "-C", str(workdir), "commit", "-m", "init", "--quiet"], check=True)

# Assert one commit exists.
log = subprocess.run(
    ["git", "-C", str(workdir), "log", "--oneline"],
    check=True, capture_output=True, text=True,
)
assert log.stdout.strip().endswith("init")
```

