## `test_interop_vim_atomic_save_dance(mount)`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-interop-6 -->
<!-- trace: skipped -->
<!-- trace_skip_reason: simulates vim's save sequence — external-tool behavior class -->

### Purpose
Vim's write flow: write new content to a temp file in the same directory, then `rename(tmp, original)`. This exercises rename-over-existing + fsync + the editor's atomic-save pattern that every serious filesystem must support.

### Postconditions

```python
target = mount / "doc.md"
target.write_text("original content\n")

# Vim-style write: write to .swp, then rename.
tmp = mount / ".doc.md.swp"
tmp.write_text("new content\n")
os.rename(tmp, target)

assert target.read_text() == "new content\n"
assert not tmp.exists()
```

